# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: audio-codec-mp3
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] In telecommunications and computing, **bit rate** (**bitrate** or as a variable *R*) is the number of bits that are conveyed or processed per unit of time.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The bit rate is expressed as **bits per second** (symbol: **bit/s**), often with an SI prefix such as kilo (1 kbit/s = 1,000 bit/s), mega (1 Mbit/s = 1,000 kbit/s), giga (1 Gbit/s = 1,000 Mbit/s) or tera (1 Tbit/s = 1,000 Gbit/s).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The non-standard abbreviation **bps** is often used: 1 Mbps is 1 Mbit/s, that is, one million bits per second.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The bit rate is different from the **transfer rate**, measured in transfers per second, when the channel is parallel and thus transfers multiple bits per transfer.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] In most computing and digital communication environments, one **byte per second** (symbol: **B/s**) corresponds to 8 bit/s (1 byte = 8 bits).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] However if stop bits, start bits, and parity bits need to be factored in, a higher number of bits per second will be required to achieve a throughput of the same number of bytes.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The binary prefixes defined by International Standard IEC 80000-13 are sometimes used: e.g., 1 KiB/s = 1024 B/s = 8192 bit/s, and 1 MiB/s = 1024 KiB/s.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The gross bit rate is related to the symbol rate or modulation rate, which is expressed in baud or symbols per second.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] More specifically, a line code (or baseband transmission scheme) representing the data using pulse-amplitude modulation with $2^{N}$ different voltage levels, can transfer N bits per pulse.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] A digital modulation method (or passband transmission scheme) using $2^{N}$ different symbols, for example $2^{N}$ amplitudes, phases or frequencies, can transfer N bits per symbol.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] In practice this upper bound can only be approached for line coding schemes and for so-called vestigial sideband digital modulation.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] where *n* is the number of parallel channels, *Mi* is the number of symbols or levels of the modulation in the *i*th channel, and *Ti* is the symbol duration time, expressed in seconds, for the *i*th channel.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] Error-correcting codes are common especially in wireless communication systems, broadband modem standards and modern copper-based high-speed LANs.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The physical layer net bitrate is the datarate measured at a reference point in the interface between the data link layer and physical layer, and may consequently include data link and higher layer overhead.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] In modems and wireless systems, link adaptation (automatic adaptation of the data rate and the modulation and/or error coding scheme to the signal quality) is often applied.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] In that context, the term **peak bitrate** denotes the net bitrate of the fastest and least robust transmission mode, used for example when the distance is very short between sender and transmitter.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] Some operating systems and network equipment may detect the "**connection speed**" (informal language) of a network access technology or communication device, implying the current net bit rate.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The term **line rate** in some textbooks is defined as gross bit rate, in others as net bit rate.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The relationship between the gross bit rate and net bit rate is affected by the FEC code rate according to the following.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The connection speed of a technology that involves forward error correction typically refers to the physical layer *net bit rate* in accordance with the above definition.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] For example, the net bitrate (and thus the "connection speed") of an IEEE 802.11a wireless network is the net bit rate of between 6 and 54 Mbit/s, while the gross bit rate is between 12 and 72 Mbit/s inclusive of error-correcting codes.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The net bit rate of ISDN2 Basic Rate Interface (2 B-channels + 1 D-channel) of 64+64+16 = 144 kbit/s also refers to the payload data rates, while the D channel signalling rate is 16 kbit/s.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The net bit rate of the Ethernet 100BASE-TX physical layer standard is 100 Mbit/s, while the gross bitrate is 125 Mbit/s, due to the 4B5B (four bit over five bit) encoding.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] In this case, the gross bit rate is equal to the symbol rate or pulse rate of 125 megabaud, due to the NRZI line code.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] In communications technologies without forward error correction and other physical layer protocol overhead, there is no distinction between gross bit rate and physical layer net bit rate.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] For example, the net as well as gross bit rate of Ethernet 10BASE-T is 10 Mbit/s.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] Due to the Manchester line code, each bit is represented by two pulses, resulting in a pulse rate of 20 megabaud.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The "connection speed" of a V.92 voiceband modem typically refers to the gross bit rate, since there is no additional error-correction code.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] It can be up to 56,000 bit/s downstream and 48,000 bit/s upstream.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] A lower bit rate may be chosen during the connection establishment phase due to adaptive modulation – slower but more robust modulation schemes are chosen in case of poor signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] Due to data compression, the actual data transmission rate or throughput (see below) may be higher.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The channel capacity, also known as the Shannon capacity, is a theoretical upper bound for the maximum net bitrate, exclusive of forward error correction coding, that is possible without bit errors for a certain physical analog node-to-node communication link.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The channel capacity is proportional to the analog bandwidth in hertz.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] This proportionality is called Hartley's law.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] Consequently, the net bit rate is sometimes called digital bandwidth capacity in bit/s.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The term *throughput*, essentially the same thing as **digital bandwidth consumption**, denotes the achieved average useful bit rate in a computer network over a logical or physical communication link or through a network node, typically measured at a reference point above the data link layer.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] This implies that the throughput often excludes data link layer protocol overhead.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The throughput is affected by the traffic load from the data source in question, as well as from other sources sharing the same network resources.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] As an example, the goodput or data transfer rate of a V.92 voiceband modem is affected by the modem physical layer and data link layer protocols.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] It is sometimes higher than the physical layer data rate due to V.44 data compression, and sometimes lower due to bit-errors and automatic repeat request retransmissions.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] In digital multimedia, bit rate represents the amount of information, or detail, that is stored per unit of time of a recording.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] Generally, choices are made about the above factors in order to achieve the desired trade-off between minimizing the bitrate and maximizing the quality of the material when it is played.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] If lossy data compression is used on audio or visual data, differences from the original signal will be introduced; if the compression is substantial, or lossy data is decompressed and recompressed, this may become noticeable in the form of compression artifacts.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] Whether these affect the perceived quality, and if so how much, depends on the compression scheme, encoder power, the characteristics of the input data, the listener's perceptions, the listener's familiarity with artifacts, and the listening or viewing environment.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The encoding bit rate of a multimedia file is its size in bytes divided by the playback time of the recording (in seconds), multiplied by eight.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] For real-time streaming multimedia, the encoding bit rate is the goodput that is required to avoid playback interruption.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The term average bitrate is used in case of variable bitrate multimedia source coding schemes.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] In this context, the *peak bit rate* is the maximum number of bits required for any short-term block of compressed data.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] A theoretical lower bound for the encoding bit rate for lossless data compression is the source information rate, also known as the *entropy rate*.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The bitrates in this section are approximately the *minimum* that the *average* listener in a typical listening or viewing environment, when using the best available compression, would perceive as not significantly worse than the reference standard.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] Compact Disc Digital Audio (CD-DA) uses 44,100 samples per second, each with a bit depth of 16, a format sometimes abbreviated like "16bit / 44.1kHz".
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] CD-DA is also stereo, using a left and right channel, so the amount of audio data per second is double that of mono, where only a single channel is used.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] where **MiB** is mebibytes with binary prefix Mi, meaning 220 = 1,048,576.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The MP3 audio format provides lossy data compression.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/bit-rate] The Advanced Audio Coding (AAC) audio format provides lossy data compression or lossless data compression.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] This overlapping, in addition to the energy-compaction qualities of the DCT, makes the MDCT especially attractive for signal compression applications, since it helps to avoid artifacts stemming from the block boundaries.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] As a result of these advantages, the MDCT is the most widely used lossy compression technique in audio data compression.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The discrete cosine transform (DCT) was first proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972, and demonstrated by Ahmed with T.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Bradley at the University of Surrey in 1987, following earlier work by Princen and Bradley (1986) to develop the MDCT's underlying principle of **time-domain aliasing cancellation** (TDAC), described below.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] In MP3, the MDCT is not applied to the audio signal directly, but rather to the output of a 32-band polyphase quadrature filter (PQF) bank.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The output of this MDCT is postprocessed by an alias reduction formula to reduce the typical aliasing of the PQF filter bank.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Such a combination of a filter bank with an MDCT is called a *hybrid* filter bank or a *subband* MDCT.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] AAC, on the other hand, normally uses a pure MDCT; only the (rarely used) MPEG-4 AAC-SSR variant (by Sony) uses a four-band PQF bank followed by an MDCT.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Similar to MP3, ATRAC uses stacked quadrature mirror filters (QMF) followed by an MDCT.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] As a lapped transform, the MDCT is somewhat unusual compared to other Fourier-related transforms in that it has half as many outputs as inputs (instead of the same number).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] In particular, it is a linear function $F\colon \mathbf {R} ^{2N}\to \mathbf {R} ^{N}$ (where **R** denotes the set of real numbers).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The normalization coefficient in front of this transform, here unity, is an arbitrary convention and differs between treatments.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Only the product of the normalizations of the MDCT and the IMDCT, below, is constrained.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The inverse MDCT is known as the **IMDCT**.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Because there are different numbers of inputs and outputs, at first glance it might seem that the MDCT should not be invertible.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] However, perfect invertibility is achieved by *adding* the overlapped IMDCTs of subsequent overlapping blocks, causing the errors to *cancel* and the original data to be retrieved; this technique is known as *time-domain aliasing cancellation* (**TDAC**).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Like for the DCT-IV, an orthogonal transform, the inverse has the same form as the forward transform.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] In the case of a windowed MDCT with the usual window normalization (see below), the normalization coefficient in front of the IMDCT should be multiplied by 2 (i.e., becoming 2/*N*).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Although the direct application of the MDCT formula would require O(*N*2) operations, it is possible to compute the same thing with only O(*N* log *N*) complexity by recursively factorizing the computation, as in the fast Fourier transform (FFT).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] One can also compute MDCTs via other transforms, typically a DFT (FFT) or a DCT, combined with O(*N*) pre- and post-processing steps.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Also, as described below, any algorithm for the DCT-IV immediately provides a method to compute the MDCT and IMDCT of even size.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] AC-3 uses a Kaiser–Bessel derived (KBD) window, and MPEG-4 AAC can also use a KBD window.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Note that windows applied to the MDCT are different from windows used for some other types of signal analysis, since they must fulfill the Princen–Bradley condition.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] One of the reasons for this difference is that MDCT windows are applied twice, for both the MDCT (analysis) and the IMDCT (synthesis).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] As can be seen by inspection of the definitions, for *even* *N* the MDCT is essentially equivalent to a DCT-IV, where the input is shifted by *N*/2 and two *N*-blocks of data are transformed at once.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] By examining this equivalence more carefully, important properties like TDAC can be easily derived.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Thus, if its inputs are an array *x* of length *N*, we can imagine extending this array to (*x*, −*x**R*, −*x*, *x**R*, ...) and so on, where *x**R* denotes *x* in reverse order.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Consider an MDCT with 2*N* inputs and *N* outputs, where we divide the inputs into four blocks (*a*, *b*, *c*, *d*) each of size *N*/2.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] If we shift these to the right by *N*/2 (from the +*N*/2 term in the MDCT definition), then (*b*, *c*, *d*) extend past the end of the *N* DCT-IV inputs, so we must "fold" them back according to the boundary conditions described above.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] In this way, any algorithm to compute the DCT-IV can be trivially applied to the MDCT.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Similarly, the IMDCT formula above is precisely 1/2 of the DCT-IV (which is its own inverse), where the output is extended (via the boundary conditions) to a length 2*N* and shifted back to the left by *N*/2.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The inverse DCT-IV would simply give back the inputs (−*c**R* − *d*, *a* − *b**R*) from above.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Half of the IMDCT outputs are thus redundant, as *b* − *a**R* = −(*a* − *b**R*)*R*, and likewise for the last two terms.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Suppose that one computes the MDCT of the subsequent, 50% overlapped, 2*N* block (*B*, *C*).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The IMDCT will then yield, analogous to the above: (*B* − *B**R*, *C* + *C**R*)/2.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] When this is added with the previous IMDCT result in the overlapping half, the reversed terms cancel and one obtains simply *B*, recovering the original data.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The origin of the term "time-domain aliasing cancellation" is now clear.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The combinations *c* − *d**R* and so on have precisely the right signs for the combinations to cancel when they are added.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] For *odd* *N* (which are rarely used in practice), *N*/2 is not an integer, so the MDCT is not simply a shift permutation of a DCT-IV.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] In this case, the additional shift by half a sample means that the MDCT/IMDCT becomes equivalent to the DCT-III/II, and the analysis is analogous to the above.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] We have seen above that the MDCT of 2*N* inputs (*a*, *b*, *c*, *d*) is equivalent to a DCT-IV of the *N* inputs (−*c**R* − *d*, *a* − *b**R*).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The DCT-IV is designed for the case where the function at the right boundary is odd, and therefore the values near the right boundary are close to 0.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] If the input signal is smooth, this is the case: the rightmost components of *a* and *b**R* are consecutive in the input sequence (*a*, *b*, *c*, *d*), and therefore their difference is small.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Let us look at the middle of the interval: if we rewrite the above expression as (−*c**R* − *d*, *a* − *b**R*) = (−*d*, *a*) − (*b*, *c*)*R*, the second term, (*b*, *c*)*R*, gives a smooth transition in the middle.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] However, in the first term, (−*d*, *a*), there is a potential discontinuity where the right end of −*d* meets the left end of *a*.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] This is the reason for using a window function that reduces the components near the boundaries of the input sequence (*a*, *b*, *c*, *d*) towards 0.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Above, the TDAC property was proved for the ordinary MDCT, showing that adding IMDCTs of subsequent blocks in their overlapping half recovers the original data.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] The derivation of this inverse property for the windowed MDCT is only slightly more complicated.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Consider two overlapping consecutive sets of 2*N* inputs (*A*,*B*) and (*B*,*C*), for blocks *A*,*B*,*C* of size *N*.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Recall from above that when $(A,B)$ and $(B,C)$ are MDCTed, IMDCTed, and added in their overlapping half, we obtain $(B+B_{R})/2+(B-B_{R})/2=B$ , the original data.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Now we suppose that we multiply *both* the MDCT inputs *and* the IMDCT outputs by a window function of length 2*N*.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] As above, we assume a symmetric window function, which is therefore of the form $(W,W_{R})$ where *W* is a length-*N* vector and *R* denotes reversal as before.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Then the Princen-Bradley condition can be written as $W^{2}+W_{R}^{2}=(1,1,\ldots )$ , with the squares and additions performed elementwise.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/modified-discrete-cosine-transform] Therefore, instead of MDCTing $(A,B)$ , we now MDCT $(WA,W_{R}B)$ (with all multiplications performed elementwise).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MPEG-1 Audio Layer III was originally defined in 1991 as one of the three possible audio codecs of the MPEG-1 standard (along with MPEG-1 Audio Layer I and MPEG-1 Audio Layer II).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] All three options were retained and further extended—defining additional bit rates and support for more audio channels (supporting surround sound—in the subsequent MPEG-2 standard).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MP3 as a file format commonly designates files containing an elementary stream of MPEG-1 Audio or MPEG-2 Audio encoded data.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Concerning audio compression, which is its most apparent element to end-users, MP3 uses lossy compression to reduce precision of encoded data and to partially discard data, allowing for a large reduction in file sizes when compared to uncompressed audio.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The combination of small size and acceptable fidelity led to a boom in the distribution of music over the Internet in the late 1990s, with MP3 serving as an enabling technology at a time when bandwidth and storage were still at a premium.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The MP3 format soon became associated with controversies surrounding copyright infringement, music piracy, and the file-ripping and sharing services MP3.com and Napster, among others.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] With the advent of portable media players (including "MP3 players"), a product category also including smartphones, MP3 support became near-universal and it remains a *de facto* standard for digital audio despite the creation of newer coding formats such as AAC.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The Moving Picture Experts Group (MPEG) designed MP3 as part of its MPEG-1, and later MPEG-2, standards.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MPEG-1 Audio (MPEG-1 Part 3), which included MPEG-1 Audio Layer I, II, and III, was approved as a committee draft for an ISO/IEC standard in 1991, finalized in 1992, and published in 1993 as ISO/IEC 11172-3:1993.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] An MPEG-2 Audio (MPEG-2 Part 3) extension with lower sample and bit rates was published in 1995 as ISO/IEC 13818-3:1995.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] It requires only minimal modifications to existing MPEG-1 decoders (recognition of the MPEG-2 bit in the header and addition of the new lower sample and bit rates).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The MP3 lossy compression algorithm takes advantage of a perceptual limitation of human hearing called auditory masking.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In 1894, the American physicist Alfred M.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Mayer reported that a tone could be rendered inaudible by another tone of lower frequency.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In 1959, Richard Ehmer described a complete set of auditory curves regarding this phenomenon.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Between 1967 and 1974, Eberhard Zwicker did work in the areas of tuning and masking of critical frequency-bands, which in turn built on the fundamental research in the area from Harvey Fletcher and his collaborators at Bell Labs.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Perceptual coding was first used for speech coding compression with linear predictive coding (LPC), which has origins in the work of Fumitada Itakura (Nagoya University) and Shuzo Saito (Nippon Telegraph and Telephone) in 1966.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Schroeder at Bell Labs proposed an LPC speech codec, called adaptive predictive coding, that used a psychoacoustic coding-algorithm exploiting the masking properties of the human ear.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Further optimization by Schroeder and Atal with J.L.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Hall was later reported in a 1979 paper.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] That same year, a psychoacoustic masking codec was also proposed by M.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Krasner, who published and produced hardware for speech (not usable as music bit-compression), but the publication of his results in a relatively obscure Lincoln Laboratory Technical Report did not immediately influence the mainstream of psychoacoustic codec-development.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The discrete cosine transform (DCT), a type of transform coding for lossy compression, proposed by Nasir Ahmed in 1972, was developed by Ahmed with T.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Rao in 1973; they published their results in 1974.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] This led to the development of the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), proposed by J.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Bradley in 1987, following earlier work by Princen and Bradley in 1986.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The MDCT later became a core part of the MP3 algorithm.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Ernst Terhardt and other collaborators constructed an algorithm describing auditory masking with high accuracy in 1982.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] This work added to a variety of reports from authors dating back to Fletcher, and to the work that initially determined critical ratios and critical bandwidths.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In 1985, Atal and Schroeder presented code-excited linear prediction (CELP), an LPC-based perceptual speech-coding algorithm with auditory masking that achieved a significant data compression ratio for its time.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] IEEE's refereed *Journal on Selected Areas in Communications* reported on a wide variety of (mostly perceptual) audio compression algorithms in 1988.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The "Voice Coding for Communications" edition published in February 1988 reported on a wide range of established, working audio bit compression technologies, some of them using auditory masking as part of their fundamental design, and several showing real-time hardware implementations.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The genesis of the MP3 technology is fully described in a paper from Professor Hans Musmann, who chaired the ISO MPEG Audio group for several years.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In December 1988, MPEG called for an audio coding standard.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In June 1989, 14 audio coding algorithms were submitted.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Because of certain similarities between these coding proposals, they were clustered into four development groups.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The first group was ASPEC, by Fraunhofer Gesellschaft, AT&T, CNET(France Telecom) and Thomson.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The second group was MUSICAM, by Matsushita, CCETT, ITT and Philips.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The third group was ATAC (ATRAC Coding), by Fujitsu, JVC, NEC and Sony.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] And the fourth group was SB-ADPCM, by NTT and BTRL.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The immediate predecessors of MP3 were "Optimum Coding in the Frequency Domain" (OCF), and Perceptual Transform Coding (PXFM).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] These two codecs, along with block-switching contributions from Thomson-Brandt, were merged into a codec named ASPEC, which was submitted to MPEG and won the quality competition, but which was rejected as too complex to implement.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The first practical implementation of an audio perceptual coder (OCF) in hardware (Krasner's hardware was too cumbersome and slow for practical use), was an implementation of a psychoacoustic transform coder based on Motorola 56000 digital signal processor (DSP) chips.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Another predecessor of the MP3 format and technology was the perceptual codec MUSICAM based on an integer arithmetics 32 sub-bands filter bank, driven by a psychoacoustic model.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] This codec incorporated into a broadcasting system using COFDM modulation was demonstrated on air and in the field with Radio Canada and CRC Canada during the NAB show (Las Vegas) in 1991.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The implementation of the audio part of this broadcasting system was based on a two-chip encoder (one for the subband transform, one for the psychoacoustic model designed by the team of G.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Stoll (IRT Germany), later known as psychoacoustic model I) and a real-time decoder using one Motorola 56001 DSP chip running an integer arithmetics software designed by Y.F.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] As a doctoral student at Germany's University of Erlangen-Nuremberg, Karlheinz Brandenburg began working on digital music compression in the early 1980s, focusing on how people perceive music.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MP3 is directly descended from OCF and PXFM, representing the outcome of the collaboration of Brandenburg — working as a postdoctoral researcher at AT&T-Bell Labs with James D.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Johnston ("JJ") of AT&T-Bell Labs — with the Fraunhofer Institute for Integrated Circuits, Erlangen (where he worked with Bernhard Grill and four other researchers – "The Original Six"), with relatively minor contributions from the MP2 branch of psychoacoustic sub-band coders.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In 1990, Brandenburg became an assistant professor at Erlangen-Nuremberg.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] While there, he continued to work on music compression with scientists at the Fraunhofer Society's Heinrich Herz Institute.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In 1993, he joined the staff of Fraunhofer IIS in Erlangen.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] An acapella version of the song "Tom's Diner" by Suzanne Vega was the first song used by Brandenburg to develop the MP3 format.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] It was used as a benchmark to see how well MP3's compression algorithm handled the human voice.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Brandenburg adopted the song for testing purposes, listening to it again and again each time he refined the compression algorithm, making sure it did not adversely affect the reproduction of Vega's voice.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Accordingly, he dubbed Vega the "Mother of MP3".
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Instrumental music had been easier to compress, but Vega's voice sounded unnatural in early versions of the format.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Brandenburg eventually met Vega and heard Tom's Diner performed live.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In 1991, two available proposals were assessed for an MPEG audio standard: MUSICAM (Masking pattern adapted Universal Subband Integrated Coding And Multiplexing) and ASPEC (Adaptive Spectral Perceptual Entropy Coding).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The MUSICAM technique, proposed by Philips (Netherlands), CCETT (France), the Institute for Broadcast Technology (Germany), and Matsushita (Japan), was chosen due to its simplicity and error robustness, as well as for its high level of computational efficiency.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The MUSICAM format, based on sub-band coding, became the basis for the MPEG Audio compression format, incorporating, for example, its frame structure, header format, sample rates, etc.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Under the chairmanship of Professor Musmann of the Leibniz University Hannover, the editing of the standard was delegated to Leon van de Kerkhof (Netherlands), Gerhard Stoll (Germany), and Yves-François Dehery (France), who worked on Layer I and Layer II.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] ASPEC was the joint proposal of AT&T Bell Laboratories, Thomson Consumer Electronics, Fraunhofer Society, and CNET.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] It provided the highest coding efficiency.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] A working group consisting of van de Kerkhof, Stoll, Leonardo Chiariglione (CSELT VP for Media), Yves-François Dehery, Karlheinz Brandenburg (Germany) and James D.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Johnston (United States) took ideas from ASPEC, integrated the filter bank from Layer II, added some of their ideas such as the joint stereo coding of MUSICAM and created the MP3 format, which was designed to achieve the same quality at 128 kbit/s as MP2 at 192 kbit/s.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The algorithms for MPEG-1 Audio Layer I, II and III were approved in 1991 and finalized in 1992 as part of MPEG-1, the first standard suite by MPEG, which resulted in the international standard **ISO/IEC 11172-3** (a.k.a.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Files or data streams conforming to this standard must handle sample rates of 48k, 44100, and 32k and continue to be supported by current MP3 players and decoders.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Thus the first generation of MP3 defined 14 × 3 = 42 interpretations of MP3 frame data structures and size layouts.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The compression efficiency of encoders is typically defined by the bit rate because the compression ratio depends on the bit depth and sampling rate of the input signal.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Nevertheless, compression ratios are often published.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] They may use the compact disc (CD) parameters as references (44.1 kHz, 2 channels at 16 bits per channel or 2×16 bit), or sometimes the Digital Audio Tape (DAT) SP parameters (48 kHz, 2×16 bit).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Compression ratios with this latter reference are higher, which demonstrates the problem with the use of the term *compression ratio* for lossy encoders.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Brandenburg used a CD recording of Suzanne Vega's song "Tom's Diner" to assess and refine the MP3 compression algorithm.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] This song was chosen because of its nearly monophonic nature and wide spectral content, making it easier to hear imperfections in the compression format during playbacks.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Some more critical audio excerpts (glockenspiel, triangle, accordion, etc.) were taken from the EBU V3/SQAM reference compact disc and have been used by professional sound engineers to assess the subjective quality of the MPEG Audio formats.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] A reference simulation software implementation, written in the C language and later known as *ISO 11172-5*, was developed (in 1991–1996) by the members of the ISO MPEG Audio committee to produce bit-compliant MPEG Audio files (Layer 1, Layer 2, Layer 3).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] It was approved as a committee draft of the ISO/IEC technical report in March 1994 and printed as document CD 11172-5 in April 1994.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] It was approved as a draft technical report (DTR/DIS) in November 1994, finalized in 1996 and published as international standard ISO/IEC TR 11172-5:1998 in 1998.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The reference software in C language was later published as a freely available ISO standard.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Working in non-real time on several operating systems, it was able to demonstrate the first real-time hardware decoding (DSP based) of compressed audio.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Some other real-time implementations of MPEG Audio encoders and decoders were available for digital broadcasting (radio DAB, television DVB) towards consumer receivers and set-top boxes.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] On 7 July 1994, the Fraunhofer Society released the first software MP3 encoder, named l3enc.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The filename extension *.mp3* was chosen by the Fraunhofer team on 14 July 1995 (the files had formerly been named *.bit*).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] With the first real-time software MP3 player WinPlay3 (released 9 September 1995) many people were able to encode and play back MP3 files on their PCs.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] A hacker nicknamed SoloH found the source code of the "dist10" MPEG reference implementation on the servers of the University of Erlangen shortly after the release.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] He integrated it within a graphical interface, enabling easy conversion from CD or WAV files, and spread it on the internet.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] This software started the widespread CD ripping and digital music distribution as MP3 over the internet.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Further work on MPEG audio was finalized in 1994 as part of the second suite of MPEG standards, MPEG-2, more formally known as international standard **ISO/IEC 13818-3** (a.k.a.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] *MPEG-2 Part 3* or backward compatible *MPEG-2 Audio* or *MPEG-2 Audio BC*), originally published in 1995.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MPEG-2 Part 3 (ISO/IEC 13818-3) defined 42 additional bit rates and sample rates for MPEG-1 Audio Layer I, II and III.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The new sampling rates are exactly half that of those originally defined in MPEG-1 Audio.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] This reduction in sampling rates serves to cut the available frequency fidelity in half while likewise cutting the bit rate by 50%.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MPEG-2 Part 3 also enhanced MPEG-1's audio by allowing the coding of audio programs with more than two channels, up to 5.1 multichannel, even though to this date no encoder is known to have used this feature.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] A third generation of "MP3" style data streams (files) extended the *MPEG-2* ideas and implementation but was named *MPEG-2.5* audio since MPEG-3 already had a different meaning.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] This extension was developed at Fraunhofer IIS by reducing the frame sync field in the MP3 header from 12 to 11 bits.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] As in the transition from MPEG-1 to MPEG-2, MPEG-2.5 adds more sampling rates exactly half of those available using MPEG-2.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] It thus widens the scope of MP3 to include human speech and other applications yet requires only 25% of the bandwidth (frequency reproduction) possible using MPEG-1 sampling rates.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] While not an ISO-recognized standard, MPEG-2.5 is widely supported by most digital audio players and computer software-based MP3 encoders (LAME), decoders (FFmpeg), and players (MPC) adding 3 × 8 = 24 additional MP3 frame types.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Each generation of MP3 thus supports 3 sampling rates exactly half that of the prior generation for a total of 9 variations of MP3 format files.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The sample rate comparison table between MPEG-1, 2, and 2.5 is given later in the article.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MPEG-2.5 is supported by LAME (since 2000), Media Player Classic (MPC), iTunes, and FFmpeg.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MPEG-2.5 was not developed by MPEG (see above) and was never approved as an international standard.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MPEG-2.5 is thus an unofficial or proprietary extension to the MP3 format.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] It is nonetheless ubiquitous and especially advantageous for low-bit-rate human speech applications.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In the second half of the 1990s, MP3 files began to spread on the Internet, often via underground pirated song networks.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The first known experiment in Internet distribution was organized in the early 1990s by the Internet Underground Music Archive, better known by the acronym IUMA.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] After some experiments using uncompressed audio files, this archive started to deliver on the native worldwide low-speed Internet some compressed MPEG Audio files using the MP2 (Layer II) format and later on used MP3 files when the standard was fully completed.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The popularity of MP3s began to rise rapidly with the advent of Nullsoft's audio player Winamp, released in 1997, which still had in 2023 a community of 80 million active users.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In November 1997, the website mp3.com was offering thousands of MP3s created by independent artists for free.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The small size of MP3 files enabled widespread peer-to-peer file sharing of music ripped from CDs, which would have formerly been nearly impossible.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The first large peer-to-peer filesharing network, Napster, was launched in 1999.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The ease of creating and sharing MP3s resulted in widespread copyright infringement.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Major record companies argued that this free sharing of music reduced sales, and called it "music piracy".
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] They reacted by pursuing lawsuits against Napster, which was eventually shut down and later sold, and against individual users who engaged in file sharing.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Napster later returned as a legitimate music streaming service.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Unauthorized MP3 file sharing continues on next-generation peer-to-peer networks.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Authorized services, such as Amazon.com, Beatport, Bleep, eMusic, Juno Records, and the reincarnated Napster, sell unrestricted music in the MP3 format.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Diagram of the structure of an MP3 file (MPEG version 2.5, not described here, changes the last bit of sync word to "0" as an indication, effectively moving one bit to the version field.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] An MP3 file is made up of MP3 frames, which consist of a header and a data block.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] This sequence of frames is called an elementary stream.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Due to the "bit reservoir", frames are not independent items and cannot usually be extracted on arbitrary frame boundaries.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The MP3 Data blocks contain the (compressed) audio information in terms of frequencies and amplitudes.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The diagram shows that the MP3 Header consists of a sync word, which is used to identify the beginning of a valid frame.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] This is followed by a bit indicating that this is the MPEG standard and two bits that indicate that layer 3 is used; hence MPEG-1 Audio Layer 3 or MP3.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] After this, the values will differ, depending on the MP3 file.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] *ISO/IEC 11172-3* defines the range of values for each section of the header along with the specification of the header.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Most MP3 files today contain ID3 metadata, which precedes or follows the MP3 frames, as noted in the diagram.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The data stream can contain an optional checksum.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Joint stereo is done only on a frame-to-frame basis.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In short, MP3 compression works by reducing the accuracy of certain components of sound that are considered (by psychoacoustic analysis) to be beyond the hearing capabilities of most humans.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] This method is commonly referred to as perceptual coding or psychoacoustic modeling.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The remaining audio information is then recorded in a space-efficient manner using MDCT and FFT algorithms.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The MP3 encoding algorithm is generally split into four parts.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Part 1 divides the audio signal into smaller pieces, called frames, and an MDCT filter is then performed on the output.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Part 2 passes the sample into a 1024-point fast Fourier transform (FFT), then the psychoacoustic model is applied and another MDCT filter is performed on the output.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Part 3 quantifies and encodes each sample, known as noise allocation, which adjusts itself to meet the bit rate and sound masking requirements.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Part 4 formats the bitstream, called an audio frame, which is made up of 4 parts, the header, error check, audio data, and ancillary data.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Each MPEG-1 MP3 frame is 1152 samples, divided into two granules of 576 samples.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] These 576 consecutive samples, initially in the time domain, are transformed in one block to 576 frequency-domain samples by MDCT.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MP3 also allows the use of shorter blocks in a granule, down to a size of 192 samples; this feature is used when a transient is detected.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Doing so limits the temporal spread of quantization noise accompanying the transient (see psychoacoustics).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Frequency resolution is limited by the small long block window size, which decreases coding efficiency.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Time resolution can be too low for highly transient signals and may cause smearing of percussive sounds.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Due to the tree structure of the filter bank, pre-echo problems are made worse, as the combined impulse response of the two filter banks does not, and cannot, provide an optimum solution in time/frequency resolution.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Additionally, the combining of the two filter banks' outputs creates aliasing problems that must be handled partially by the "aliasing compensation" stage; however, that creates excess energy to be coded in the frequency domain, thereby decreasing coding efficiency.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Decoding, on the other hand, is carefully defined in the standard.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Most decoders are "bitstream compliant", which means that the decompressed output that they produce from a given MP3 file will be the same, within a specified degree of rounding tolerance, as the output specified mathematically in the ISO/IEC high standard document (ISO/IEC 11172-3).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Therefore, the comparison of decoders is usually based on how computationally efficient they are (i.e., how much memory or CPU time they use in the decoding process).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Over time this concern has become less of an issue as CPU clock rates transitioned from MHz to GHz.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Encoder/decoder overall delay is not defined, which means there is no official provision for gapless playback.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] However, some encoders such as LAME can attach additional metadata that will allow players that can handle it to deliver seamless playback.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] When performing lossy audio encoding, such as creating an MP3 data stream, there is a trade-off between the amount of data generated and the sound quality of the results.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The person generating an MP3 selects a bit rate, which specifies how many kilobits per second of audio is desired.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The higher the bit rate, the larger the MP3 data stream will be, and, generally, the closer it will sound to the original recording.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] With too low a bit rate, compression artifacts (i.e., sounds that were not present in the original recording) may be audible in the reproduction.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Some audio is hard to compress because of its randomness and sharp attacks.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] When this type of audio is compressed, artifacts such as ringing or pre-echo are usually heard.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] A sample of applause or a triangle instrument with a relatively low bit rate provides good examples of compression artifacts.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Most subjective testings of perceptual codecs tend to avoid using these types of sound materials, however, the artifacts generated by percussive sounds are barely perceptible due to the specific temporal masking feature of the 32-sub-band filterbank of Layer II on which the format is based.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The MPEG-1 standard does not include a precise specification for an MP3 encoder but does provide examples of psychoacoustic models, rate loops, and the like in the non-normative part of the original standard.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] When this was written, the suggested implementations were quite dated.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Implementers of the standard were supposed to devise algorithms suitable for removing parts of the information from the audio input.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] As a result, many different MP3 encoders became available, each producing files of differing quality.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Comparisons were widely available, so it was easy for a prospective user of an encoder to research the best choice.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Some encoders that were proficient at encoding at higher bit rates (such as LAME) were not necessarily as good at lower bit rates.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Besides the bit rate of an encoded piece of audio, the quality of MP3-encoded sound also depends on the quality of the encoder algorithm as well as the complexity of the signal being encoded.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] As the MP3 standard allows quite a bit of freedom with encoding algorithms, different encoders do feature quite different quality, even with identical bit rates.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] As an example, in a public listening test featuring two early MP3 encoders set at about 128 kbit/s, one scored 3.66 on a 1–5 scale, while the other scored only 2.22.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Quality is dependent on the choice of encoder and encoding parameters.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] This observation caused a revolution in audio encoding.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Early on bit rate was the prime and only consideration.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] At the time MP3 files were of the very simplest type: they used the same bit rate for the entire file: this process is known as constant bit rate (CBR) encoding.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Using a constant bit rate makes encoding simpler and less CPU-intensive.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] However, it is also possible to optimize the size of the file by creating files where the bit rate changes throughout the file.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The bit reservoir and VBR encoding were part of the original MPEG-1 standard.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The concept behind them is that, in any piece of audio, some sections are easier to compress, such as silence or music containing only a few tones, while others will be more difficult to compress.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] So, the overall quality of the file may be increased by using a lower bit rate for the less complex passages and a higher one for the more complex parts.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] With some advanced MP3 encoders, it is possible to specify a given quality, and the encoder will adjust the bit rate accordingly.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Users that desire a particular "quality setting" that is transparent to their ears can use this value when encoding all of their music, and generally speaking not need to worry about performing personal listening tests on each piece of music to determine the correct bit rate.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Perceived quality can be influenced by the listening environment (ambient noise), listener attention, listener training, and in most cases by listener audio equipment (such as sound cards, speakers, and headphones).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Furthermore, sufficient quality may be achieved by a lesser quality setting for lectures and human speech applications and reduces encoding time and complexity.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] A test given to new students by Stanford University Music Professor Jonathan Berger showed that student preference for MP3-quality music has risen each year.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Berger said the students seem to prefer the 'sizzle' sounds that MP3s bring to music.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] An in-depth study of MP3 audio quality, sound artist and composer Ryan Maguire's project "The Ghost in the MP3" isolates the sounds lost during MP3 compression.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In 2015, he released the track "moDernisT" (an anagram of "Tom's Diner"), composed exclusively from the sounds deleted during MP3 compression of the song "Tom's Diner", the track originally used in the formulation of the MP3 standard.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] A detailed account of the techniques used to isolate the sounds deleted during MP3 compression, along with the conceptual motivation for the project, was published in the 2014 Proceedings of the International Computer Music Conference.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Earlier systems also lack fast forwarding and rewinding playback controls on MP3.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MPEG-1 frames contain the most detail in 320 kbit/s mode, the highest allowable bit rate setting, with silence and simple tones still requiring 32 kbit/s.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MPEG-2 frames can capture up to 12 kHz sound reproductions needed up to 160 kbit/s.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] A sample rate of 44.1 kHz is commonly used for music reproduction because this is also used for CD audio, the main source used for creating MP3 files.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] A great variety of bit rates are used on the Internet.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] A bit rate of 128 kbit/s is commonly used, at a compression ratio of 11:1, offering adequate audio quality in a relatively small space.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] As Internet bandwidth availability and hard drive sizes have increased, higher bit rates up to 320 kbit/s are widespread.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Uncompressed audio as stored on an audio-CD has a bit rate of 1,411.2 kbit/s, (16 bit/sample × 44,100 samples/second × 2 channels / 1,000 bits/kilobit), so the bit rates 128, 160, and 192 kbit/s represent compression ratios of approximately 11:1, 9:1 and 7:1 respectively.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Non-standard bit rates up to 640 kbit/s can be achieved with the LAME encoder and the free format option, although few MP3 players can play those files.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] According to the ISO standard, decoders are only required to be able to decode streams up to 320 kbit/s.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Early MPEG Layer III encoders used what is now called constant bit rate (CBR).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The software was only able to use a uniform bit rate on all frames in an MP3 file.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Later more sophisticated MP3 encoders were able to use the bit reservoir to target an average bit rate selecting the encoding rate for each frame based on the complexity of the sound in that portion of the recording.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] A more sophisticated MP3 encoder can produce variable bit rate audio.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MPEG audio may use bit rate switching on a per-frame basis, but only layer III decoders must support it.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] VBR is used when the goal is to achieve a fixed level of quality.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The final file size of a VBR encoding is less predictable than with constant bit rate.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Average bit rate is a type of VBR implemented as a compromise between the two: the bit rate is allowed to vary for more consistent quality, but is controlled to remain near an average value chosen by the user, for predictable file sizes.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Although an MP3 decoder must support VBR to be standards compliant, historically some decoders have bugs with VBR decoding, particularly before VBR encoders became widespread.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Layer III audio can also use a "bit reservoir", a partially full frame's ability to hold part of the next frame's audio data, allowing temporary changes in effective bit rate, even in a constant bit rate stream.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The ancillary data field can be used to store user-defined data.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The ancillary data is optional and the number of bits available is not explicitly given.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The ancillary data is located after the Huffman code bits and ranges to where the next frame's main_data_begin points to.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Encoder mp3PRO used ancillary data to encode extra information which could improve audio quality when decoded with its algorithm.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] A "tag" in an audio file is a section of the file that contains metadata such as the title, artist, album, track number, or other information about the file's contents.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The MP3 standards do not define tag formats for MP3 files, nor is there a standard container format that would support metadata and obviate the need for tags.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] However, several *de facto* standards for tag formats exist.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] As of 2010, the most widespread are ID3v1 and ID3v2, and the more recently introduced APEv2.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] These tags are normally embedded at the beginning or end of MP3 files, separate from the actual MP3 frame data.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MP3 decoders either extract information from the tags or just treat them as ignorable, non-MP3 junk data.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Playing and editing software often contains tag editing functionality, but there are also tag editor applications dedicated to the purpose.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Aside from metadata about the audio content, tags may also be used for DRM.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] ReplayGain is a standard for measuring and storing the loudness of an MP3 file (audio normalization) in its metadata tag, enabling a ReplayGain-compliant player to automatically adjust the overall playback volume for each file.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MP3Gain may be used to reversibly modify files based on ReplayGain measurements so that adjusted playback can be achieved on players without ReplayGain capability.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The basic MP3 decoding and encoding technology is patent-free in the European Union, all patents having expired there by 2012 at the latest.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In the United States, the technology became substantially patent-free on 16 April 2017 (see below).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MP3 patents expired in the US between 2007 and 2017.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In the past, many organizations have claimed ownership of patents related to MP3 decoding or encoding.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] These claims led to several legal threats and actions from a variety of sources.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] As a result, in countries that allow software patents, uncertainty about which patents must have been licensed to create MP3 products without committing patent infringement was common in the early stages of the technology's adoption.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The initial near-complete MPEG-1 standard (parts 1, 2, and 3) was publicly available on 6 December 1991 as ISO CD 11172.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In most countries, patents cannot be filed after prior art has been made public, and patents expire 20 years after the initial filing date, which can be up to 12 months later for filings in other countries.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] As a result, patents required to implement MP3 expired in most countries by December 2012, 21 years after the publication of ISO CD 11172.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] An exception is the United States, where patents in force but filed before 8 June 1995 expire after the later of 17 years from the issue date or 20 years from the priority date.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] A lengthy patent prosecution process may result in a patent issued much later than normally expected (see submarine patents).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The various MP3-related patents expired on dates ranging from 2007 to 2017 in the United States.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Patents for anything disclosed in ISO CD 11172 filed a year or more after its publication are questionable.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] If only the known MP3 patents filed by December 1992 are considered, then MP3 decoding has been patent-free in the US since 22 September 2015, when U.S. patent 5,812,672, which had a PCT filing in October 1992, expired.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] If the longest-running patent mentioned in the aforementioned references is taken as a measure, then the MP3 technology became patent-free in the United States on 16 April 2017, when U.S. patent 6,009,399, held and administered by Technicolor, expired.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Technicolor (formerly named Thomson Consumer Electronics) claimed to control MP3 licensing of the Layer 3 patents in many countries, including the United States, Japan, Canada, and EU countries.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Technicolor had been actively enforcing these patents.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] MP3 license revenues from Technicolor's administration generated about €100 million for the Fraunhofer Society in 2005.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In September 1998, the Fraunhofer Institute sent a letter to several developers of MP3 software stating that a license was required to "distribute and/or sell decoders and/or encoders".
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The letter claimed that unlicensed products "infringe the patent rights of Fraunhofer and Thomson.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] To make, sell or distribute products using the [MPEG Layer-3] standard and thus our patents, you need to obtain a license under these patents from us." This led to the situation where the LAME MP3 encoder project could not offer its users official binaries that could run on their computer.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The project's position was that as source code, LAME was simply a description of how an MP3 encoder *could* be implemented.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Unofficially, compiled binaries were available from other sources.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Sisvel S.p.A., a Luxembourg-based company, administers licenses for patents applying to MPEG Audio.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] They, along with its United States subsidiary Audio MPEG, Inc. had previously sued Thomson for patent infringement on MP3 technology, but those disputes were resolved in November 2005 with Sisvel granting Thomson a license to their patents.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Motorola followed soon after and signed with Sisvel to license MP3-related patents in December 2005.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Except for three patents, the US patents administered by Sisvel had all expired in 2015.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] As of around the first quarter of 2023, Sisvel's licensing program has become a legacy.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In September 2006, German officials seized MP3 players from SanDisk's booth at the IFA show in Berlin after an Italian patents firm won an injunction on behalf of Sisvel against SanDisk in a dispute over licensing rights.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The injunction was later reversed by a Berlin judge, but that reversal was in turn blocked the same day by another judge from the same court, "bringing the Patent Wild West to Germany" in the words of one commentator.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In February 2007, Texas MP3 Technologies sued Apple, Samsung Electronics and Sandisk in eastern Texas federal court, claiming infringement of a portable MP3 player patent that Texas MP3 said it had been assigned.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Apple, Samsung, and Sandisk all settled the claims against them in January 2009.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Alcatel-Lucent has asserted several MP3 coding and compression patents, allegedly inherited from AT&T-Bell Labs, in litigation of its own.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] In November 2006, before the companies' merger, Alcatel sued Microsoft for allegedly infringing seven patents.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] On 23 February 2007, a San Diego jury awarded Alcatel-Lucent US $1.52 billion in damages for infringement of two of them.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] The court subsequently revoked the award, however, finding that one patent had not been infringed and that the other was not owned by Alcatel-Lucent; it was co-owned by AT&T and Fraunhofer, who had licensed it to Microsoft, the judge ruled.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] That defense judgment was upheld on appeal in 2008.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Among these, Advanced Audio Coding (AAC) is the most widely used, and was designed to be the successor to MP3.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] There also exist other lossy formats such as mp3PRO and MP2.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] They are members of the same technological family as MP3 and depend on roughly similar psychoacoustic models and MDCT algorithms.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Whereas MP3 uses a hybrid coding approach that is part MDCT and part FFT, AAC is purely MDCT, significantly improving compression efficiency.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Many of the basic patents underlying these formats are held by Fraunhofer Society, Alcatel-Lucent, Thomson Consumer Electronics, Bell, Dolby, LG Electronics, NEC, NTT Docomo, Panasonic, Sony, ETRI, JVC Kenwood, Philips, Microsoft, and NTT.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Microsoft created and promoted their own competing standard, Windows Media Audio (WMA) with the claim that it is better than MP3.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] When the digital audio player market was taking off, MP3 was widely adopted as the standard hence the popular name "MP3 player".
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Sony was an exception and used their own ATRAC codec taken from their MiniDisc format, which Sony claimed was better.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Following criticism and lower than expected Walkman sales, in 2004 Sony for the first time introduced native MP3 support to its Walkman players.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] There are also open compression formats like Opus and Vorbis (OGG) that are available free of charge and without any known patent restrictions.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Besides lossy compression methods, lossless formats are a significant alternative to MP3 because they provide unaltered audio content, though with an increased file size compared to lossy compression.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/mp3] Lossless formats include FLAC (Free Lossless Audio Codec), Apple Lossless and many others.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/perceptual-coding] Perceptual coding is based on models of human hearing and vision, such as those studied in psychoacoustics and psychovisual research.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/perceptual-coding] By discarding or reducing components of a signal that fall below perceptual thresholds, it achieves significant reductions in bit rate while maintaining a subjectively acceptable quality.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/perceptual-coding] The principles of perceptual coding were applied in analog communication systems long before the advent of digital media.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/perceptual-coding] These analog systems demonstrated the effectiveness of tailoring transmission to the characteristics of human perception, laying the groundwork for digital perceptual coding methods.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/perceptual-coding] Research in the 1970s and 1980s on psychoacoustics and psychovisual modeling provided the basis for digital perceptual coding.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/perceptual-coding] In audio, this led to the late-1980s development of the MPEG audio formats (such as MP3), which achieved major reductions in bit rate by discarding inaudible sound components.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/perceptual-coding] At the same time, the MPEG standards applied similar principles to video, using techniques such as chroma subsampling and motion-adaptive coding.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/perceptual-coding] During the 1990s and 2000s, perceptual coding was embedded in widely used formats including AAC, MPEG-2 video, and H.264/AVC, supporting the rise of digital media distribution on CDs, DVDs, and early internet platforms.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/perceptual-coding] More recent codecs, such as HEVC, AV1, and Opus, continue to refine perceptual models to balance compression efficiency with quality on modern networks and devices.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/perceptual-coding] Perceptual coding draws directly on psychoacoustics (the study of auditory perception) and psychovisual research (the study of visual perception).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/perceptual-coding] These disciplines provide the models that determine which parts of a signal can be safely removed without affecting perceived quality.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Hearing is not a purely mechanical phenomenon of wave propagation, but is also a sensory and perceptual event.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] When a person hears something, that something arrives at the ear as a mechanical sound wave traveling through the air, but within the ear it is transformed into neural action potentials.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] These nerve pulses then travel to the brain where they are perceived.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Hence, in many problems in acoustics, such as for audio processing, it is advantageous to take into account not just the mechanics of the environment, but also the fact that both the ear and the brain are involved in a person's listening experience.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The inner ear, for example, does significant signal processing in converting sound waveforms into neural stimuli, this processing renders certain differences between waveforms imperceptible.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Data compression techniques, such as MP3, make use of this fact.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] In addition, the ear has a nonlinear response to sounds of different intensity levels; this nonlinear response is called loudness.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Telephone networks and audio noise reduction systems make use of this fact by nonlinearly compressing data samples before transmission and then expanding them for playback.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Another effect of the ear's nonlinear response is that sounds that are close in frequency produce phantom beat notes, or intermodulation distortion products.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] There are at least five features to identify effective psychoacoustic practices: Loudness (the measures of perceived volume), Roughness (sensory dissonance), Sharpness (spectral distribution), Tonalness (the ratio of tonal spectral peaks), and Spaciousness (to predict perceived Spaciousness).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Another procedure for recognizing music genres or recommending music is to remove a wide range of objective features that are not entirely related to human perception.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] However, there are some low level features that aren't related to human/physical perception, but can improve the discovery of psychoacoustics.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The first one, Root Mean Square (RMS), is another way how sound can be measured, specifically loudness.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] RMS is a significant process of measurement because it helps people monitor volume.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Spectral Rolloff helps guide the frequency to a balance.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Spectral Flatness is considered to outline how loud or quite a noise range.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Lastly, Inter Channel Cross Correlation estimates the relationship between how one ear perceived sound in relation to the other ear.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The human ear can nominally hear sounds in the range 20 to 20000 Hz.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The upper limit tends to decrease with age; most adults are unable to hear above 16000 Hz.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Under ideal laboratory conditions, the lowest frequency that has been identified as a musical tone is 12 Hz.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Tones between 4 and 16 Hz can be perceived via the body's sense of touch.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Human perception of audio signal time separation has been measured to be less than 10 μs.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] This does not mean that frequencies above 100 kHz (1/10 μs) are audible, but that time discrimination is not directly coupled with frequency range.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Frequency resolution of the ear is about 3.6 Hz within the octave of 1000–2000 Hz That is, changes in pitch larger than 3.6 Hz can be perceived in a clinical setting.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] However, even smaller pitch differences can be perceived through other means.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] For example, the interference of two pitches can often be heard as a repetitive variation in the volume of the tone.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] This amplitude modulation occurs with a frequency equal to the difference in frequencies of the two tones and is known as beating.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The semitone scale used in Western musical notation is not a linear frequency scale but logarithmic.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The intensity range of audible sounds is enormous.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Human eardrums are sensitive to variations in sound pressure and can detect pressure changes from as small as a few micropascals (μPa) to greater than 100 kPa.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] For this reason, sound pressure level is also measured logarithmically, with all pressures referenced to 20 μPa (or 1.97385×10−10 atm).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The lower limit of audibility is therefore defined as 0 dB, but the upper limit is not as clearly defined.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The upper limit is more a question of the potential to cause noise-induced hearing loss.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] A more rigorous exploration of the lower limits of audibility determines that the minimum threshold at which a sound can be heard is frequency dependent.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] By measuring this minimum intensity for test tones of various frequencies, a frequency-dependent absolute threshold of hearing (ATH) curve may be derived.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Typically, the ear shows a peak of sensitivity (i.e., its lowest ATH) between 1–5 kHz, though the threshold changes with age, with older ears showing decreased sensitivity above 2 kHz.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The ATH is the lowest of the equal-loudness contours.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Equal-loudness contours indicate the sound pressure level (dB SPL), over the range of audible frequencies that are perceived as being of equal loudness.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Equal-loudness contours were first measured by Fletcher and Munson at Bell Labs in 1933 using pure tones reproduced via headphones, and the data they collected are called Fletcher–Munson curves.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Because subjective loudness was difficult to measure, the Fletcher–Munson curves were averaged over many subjects.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Robinson and Dadson refined the process in 1956 to obtain a new set of equal-loudness curves for a frontal sound source measured in an anechoic chamber.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The Robinson-Dadson curves were standardized as ISO 226 in 1986.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] In 2003, ISO 226 was revised using data collected from 12 international studies.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Sound localization is the process of determining the location of a sound source.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The brain utilizes subtle differences in loudness, tone and timing between the two ears to allow us to localize sound sources.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Localization can be described in terms of three-dimensional position: the azimuth or horizontal angle, the zenith or vertical angle, and the distance (for static sounds) or velocity (for moving sounds).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Humans, as most four-legged animals, are adept at detecting direction in the horizontal, but less so in the vertical directions due to the ears being placed symmetrically.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Some species of owls have their ears placed asymmetrically and can detect sound in all three planes, an adaptation to hunt small mammals in the dark.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Suppose a listener can hear a given acoustical signal under silent conditions.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] When a signal is playing while another sound is being played, the signal has to be stronger for the listener to hear it.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The interfering signal is known as the *masker* and the impeded listening, *masking*.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The masker does not need to have the frequency components of the original signal for masking to happen.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] A masked signal can be heard even though it is weaker than the masker.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Masking happens when a signal and a masker are played together—for instance, when one person whispers while another person shouts—and the listener doesn't hear the weaker signal as it has been masked by the louder masker.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Masking can also happen to a signal before a masker starts or after a masker stops.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] For example, a sudden loud clap sound can make sounds inaudible immediately preceding or following.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The effect of backward masking is weaker than forward masking.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The masking effect has been widely studied in psychoacoustical research and are exploited in lossy audio encoding, such as MP3.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] When presented with a harmonic series of frequencies in the relationship 2*f*, 3*f*, 4*f*, 5*f*, etc.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] (where *f* is a specific frequency), humans tend to perceive that the pitch is *f*.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] An audible example can be found on YouTube.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Psychoacoustics includes topics and studies that are relevant to music psychology and music therapy.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Theorists such as Benjamin Boretz consider some of the results of psychoacoustics to be meaningful only in a musical context.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Irv Teibel's *Environments series* LPs (1969–79) are an early example of commercially available sounds released expressly for enhancing psychological abilities.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Psychoacoustics has long enjoyed a symbiotic relationship with computer science.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Licklider and Bob Taylor both completed graduate-level work in psychoacoustics, while BBN Technologies originally specialized in consulting on acoustics issues before it began building the first packet-switched network.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Licklider wrote a paper entitled "A duplex theory of pitch perception".
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Psychoacoustics is applied within many fields of software development, where developers map proven and experimental mathematical patterns in digital signal processing.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Many audio compression codecs such as MP3 and Opus use a psychoacoustic model to increase compression ratios.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The success of conventional audio systems for the reproduction of music in theatres and homes can be attributed to psychoacoustics and psychoacoustic considerations gave rise to novel audio systems, such as psychoacoustic sound field synthesis.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Furthermore, scientists have experimented with limited success in creating new acoustic weapons, which emit frequencies that may impair, harm, or kill.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Psychoacoustics are also leveraged in sonification to make multiple independent data dimensions audible and easily interpretable.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] This enables auditory guidance without the need for spatial audio and in sonification computer games and other applications, such as drone flying and image-guided surgery.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] It is also applied today within music, where musicians and artists continue to create new auditory experiences by masking unwanted frequencies of instruments, causing other frequencies to be enhanced.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Yet another application is in the design of small or lower-quality loudspeakers, which can use the phenomenon of missing fundamentals to give the effect of bass notes at lower frequencies than the loudspeakers are physically able to produce (see references).
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Automobile manufacturers engineer their engines and even doors to have a certain sound.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] The psychoacoustic model provides for high-quality lossy signal compression by describing which parts of a given digital audio signal can be removed or reproduced with reduced quality without significant loss in the perceived quality of the sound.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] This provides great benefit to the overall compression ratio, and psychoacoustic analysis routinely leads to compressed music files that are one-tenth to one-twelfth the size of high-quality masters, but with discernibly less proportional quality loss.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Such compression is a feature of nearly all modern lossy audio compression formats.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Some of these formats include Dolby Digital (AC-3), MP3, Opus, Ogg Vorbis, AAC, WMA, MPEG-1 Layer II (used for digital audio broadcasting in several countries), and ATRAC, the compression used in MiniDisc and some Walkman models.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Psychoacoustics is based heavily on human anatomy, especially the ear's limitations in perceiving sound as outlined previously.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] A compression algorithm can assign a lower priority to sounds outside the range of human hearing and reduce the precision of different frequencies according to the predicted masking level.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] By carefully shifting bits away from the unimportant components and toward the important ones, the algorithm ensures that the sounds a listener is most likely to perceive are most accurately represented.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Audio encoders analyse audio using a perceptual model (psychoacoustic model), in order to compute the required precision per frequency band or temporal section.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] Results of this computation are then used to adjust coding precision as a function of frequency and time through a set of coding tools that are dependent on the audio encoding format, as different formats support different coding tools.
[src:audio-codec-mp3/psychoacoustics] In many encoders, a rate control algorithm ensures that the resulting bitrate of the coded audio is within defined limits.
